UPDATE articles SET translations = jsonb_build_object('en', '{"title": "2025.9.21 Thoughts", "summary": "What kind of words can a frivolous person write?\nIt’s really hard for me to calm down because my clothes are so patchy under the patches.\n\nI am a person who is easily disappointed\nAs the saying goes, the greater the hope, the greater the disappointment. I always think of the best in everything (actually I didn’t expect the bad). Self-paralysis, like...", "content": "What kind of words can a frivolous person write?\nIt’s really hard for me to calm down because my clothes are so patchy under the patches.\n\nI am a person who is easily disappointed\nAs the saying goes, the greater the hope, the greater the disappointment. I always think of the best in everything (actually I didn’t expect the bad). Self-paralysis, just like someone told me that I will go to the paradise after death, I just said hmm, that is very free.\nTherefore, disappointment follows closely. A person with too rich imagination will dream up everything he should not have. Some people want rights, some want money, some want freedom... In fact, there are levels of delusion. The lowest level is called lust, and the highest level is called eternity.\n\nI am a complex person\nMy mind is busy and bustling with all kinds of thoughts. A gust of wind can bring you matcha-flavored ice cream or sashimi covered in wasabi sauce. Every time the mustard comes, the person''s body feels like it''s being strangled, it''s hard to breathe, and oxygen can only be used to stay alive.\nThe dandelions are floating, and they don’t know where they will scatter.\n\nI''m a strange person\nI turned off the WeChat notification sound, but still stared at the notification bar above my phone.\nI always sort out the fragments of my friends at midnight and tell them not to hold back their sadness but to say it, but I don’t know where to start talking about my powerlessness.\nI always feel like everyone treats me well, but the ending always disappoints me. In the end, I just felt that I was clumsy and stubborn.\n\nI am a reckless person\nI was reckless and bumped into my friends. Someone wraps me up with his tenderness and warmth, and someone bounces me back like a trampoline, or maybe it''s like the south wall. I hurt the enemy eight hundred and lose a thousand to myself, so I dispersed myself early.\nI''m glad that I have friends, some of whom I have no contact with, but when he is there, I know that he is the person of my choice in both directions.\n\nI am a selfish person\nI always want to get something, and desire is directly proportional to my vision. When I change from a small cage to a big one, I feel that I should get more than what I originally got. They are all tied up, and the harder they are, the tighter they become.\nBeing cute is not necessarily directly proportional to being loved. Short-term companionship is a favor, and eternity is the most difficult kind of delusion.\n\nI am a sober person\nWhen people watch from the sidelines, they are clear, and so are the authorities.\nIt’s just that being sober can’t stop this person from hitting the wall hhhh\nI am no longer surprised when anyone leaves. Both parties in the divorced relationship are mentally prepared to start a life without the other person.\n\nThis person has felt since he was a child that good night can only be said to the person he likes, and love words can only be said to one person, as if he has identified himself with a person. But later he said good night to ambiguous people and made lewd remarks. After the silence, he began to doubt whether he had turned into the person he hated most when he was a child. Later, he comforted himself that being affectionate was just a self-defense behavior of someone who longed to be loved deeply, and it was also a prayer for recognition. So alive and well, this person begins to doubt whether he is qualified to have a normal relationship.\nDon''t know\nDon''t know why."}'::jsonb) WHERE id = 2;

UPDATE articles SET translations = jsonb_build_object('en', '{"title": "Vibe coding giants", "summary": "1. Antigravity Tools is responsible for providing ammunition for Gemini 3, Cluade and other models\n2. CC Switch is responsible for taking over Claude Code, Gemini Cli and Code configuration\n...", "content": "1. Antigravity Tools is responsible for providing ammunition for Gemini 3, Cluade and other models\n2. CC Switch is responsible for taking over Claude Code, Gemini Cli and Code configuration\n3. Alma takes over the Cluade Code, Gemini Cli and Codex Cli through the ACP protocol and is responsible for the vibe Coding entrance"}'::jsonb) WHERE id = 3;

UPDATE articles SET translations = jsonb_build_object('en', '{"title": "Blog Beginning", "summary": "I would like to use this article to encourage myself. The road is long and difficult, and too many thoughts will confuse one''s ambitions. All those who follow it will be invincible.", "content": "I have newly deployed my own blog and have read a lot of other people''s blogs. I am very lucky to have such a way to have my own place on the Internet. I hope 2026 will be a leap year!\n![Picture](https://ccjtjpwzkchsqoxdrxap.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/uploads/gallery/1767541890564-d9u5hdp7h9q.png)\n\n![Picture](https://ccjtjpwzkchsqoxdrxap.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/uploads/gallery/1767541836785-mq4f9ecazj.png)\n![Picture](https://ccjtjpwzkchsqoxdrxap.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/uploads/gallery/1767541980951-xs1coqqfb4.png)\n\n![Picture](https://ccjtjpwzkchsqoxdrxap.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/uploads/gallery/1767542127786-p7tyrg63b.png)\n\n![Picture](https://ccjtjpwzkchsqoxdrxap.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/uploads/gallery/1767541998523-mncbo7s75qi.png)"}'::jsonb) WHERE id = 4;

UPDATE articles SET translations = jsonb_build_object('en', '{"title": "2026.01.08", "summary": "Tired of socializing. I don’t want to study, so I took a nap in the afternoon, so I can only start studying at eight or nine now...", "content": "Tired of socializing. I don’t want to study, so I took a nap in the afternoon, so I can only start studying now at eight or nine o’clock."}'::jsonb) WHERE id = 5;

UPDATE articles SET translations = jsonb_build_object('en', '{"title": "Summary of Teacher Baoyu’s article", "summary": "Junior developers: Treat AI as a learning tool, not a crutch. When the AI ​​suggests code, understand why it works and identify its weaknesses. Occasionally turn off the AI ​​and write key algorithms freehand. Solid CS foundation: data structure, algorithm, complexity, memory management. Do the project twice: once with...", "content": "Junior developers: Treat AI as a learning tool, not a crutch. When the AI ​​suggests code, understand why it works and identify its weaknesses. Occasionally turn off the AI ​​and write key algorithms freehand. Solid CS foundation: data structure, algorithm, complexity, memory management. Do the project twice: once with AI and once with your bare hands, and compare the differences. Learn Prompt Engineering and master the tools. Deliberately practice rigorous testing: write unit tests, understand stack traces (don’t ask the AI ​​at first glance), and use the debugger proficiently. Deeply cultivate the soft power that AI cannot replicate: system design, user experience intuition, and concurrent reasoning. Show that you can use AI to produce extremely fast results, and also turn the tide when AI stalls.\n\nBe a T-shaped talent integrating software engineering, system architecture and product strategy"}'::jsonb) WHERE id = 6;

UPDATE articles SET translations = jsonb_build_object('en', '{"title": "Superpowers comprehensive skills library", "summary": "You only know three Superpowers skills? Then you have really discovered a treasure now!\n\nNext, I will introduce to you a comprehensive skills library that provides proven technologies, patterns and workflows for CC - superpowers.\n\nIn this article I...", "content": "You only know three Superpowers skills? Then you have really discovered a treasure now!\n\nNext, I will introduce to you a comprehensive skills library that provides proven technologies, patterns and workflows for CC - superpowers.\n\nIn this article, I will comprehensively introduce all the skills of superpowers, which can be used for complex project development and delivery, so that even novices can get started quickly!\n\n(Due to a bug in Claudecode, only three commonly used skills will be displayed after downloading, and the others need to be called manually)\n\nWhy do you need Superpowers?\n\nNow the problem of AI assistant appears in:\n\nCan be done but not accomplished: Can write a bunch of seemingly reasonable steps, but lacks clear acceptance criteria, pre-dependence, and the definition of \"when it is done, it is completed.\" The result is that it goes in circles and becomes more and more scattered.\n\nContext drift: As the task gets longer, the original goal is forgotten, changed to another requirement, unable to focus on one worktree; or functions are constantly added in order to \"look smart\", and finally deviate from the main line.\n\nLack of quality gates: Many systems lack systematic verification, or the verification steps and logic are incomplete, resulting in unstable output and frequent rework.\n\nThe advantage of Superpowers is: it does not solve the problem of \"smarter\", but \"more controllable and better deliverable\".\n\nFirst select a general process (the 3 most commonly used entrances)\n\n/superpowers:brainstorming\n\nWhen to use it: You haven’t figured out what to do yet, there are many plans, and the demand is unstable.\nOutput: direction/comparison of options/risks/trade-offs.\nDon’t mess with anyone: don’t use it to write implementation plans directly (that’s writing-plans).\n\n/superpowers:writing-plans\n\nWhen to use it: The requirements are basically determined and ready to be started, but the tasks have not been broken down yet.\nOutputs: Phased plan, milestones, acceptance criteria.\nNot to be confused with: executing-plans.\n\n/superpowers:subagent-driven-development\n\nWhen to use: The task is relatively large and suitable for splitting into multiple subtasks for parallel advancement (front-end/back-end/DB/test/documentation).\nOutput: Multiple sub-agents are each responsible for a piece, and finally summarized.\nNot to be confused with: dispatching-parallel-agents (which is more like a generic version of \"process a batch of independent tasks in parallel\").\n\nNext, let’s talk about other skills used in complex work scenarios:\n\n1 Parallel correlation: these two are most similar to\n\n/superpowers:dispatching-parallel-agents\n\nWhen to use: You have a bunch of small tasks that are independent of each other: such as \"write 3 components + make up 5 unit tests + check 2 bugs + write README\".\nFeatures: More of a \"concurrent execution list\".\n\n/superpowers:subagent-driven-development\n\nWhen to use it: What you want to do is \"one function\", but it contains the collaboration of multiple modules: such as \"doing login/payment/permissions/auditing\", which can be assigned to sub-agents by module.\nFeatures: More of a \"division of labor and collaboration to create a project/feature\".\n\nOne sentence to distinguish:\ndispatching = “doing multiple independent things together”\nsubagent-driven = “A big thing is broken into several pieces and done together”\n\n2 Plan related: These two are also very similar\n\n/superpowers:writing-plans\n\nWhen to use: Write a plan (before doing it).\nOutputs: Roadmap, step-by-step, acceptance points.\n\n/superpowers:executing-plans\n\nWhen to use it: You already have a plan/steps, now it’s time to “go through the steps and record progress.”\nOutput: the results of each step, problems encountered, and the next step.\n\nOne sentence to distinguish: writing = designing the route; executing = taking the route.\n\n3 Test/verification related: It seems to be repeated, but it is actually at a different level\n\n/superpowers:test-driven-development\n\nWhen to use: You want to use TDD to do functions: first write failing tests → implement → pass → refactor.\nSuitable for: complex logic, high risk of regression, and you want to ensure quality.\n\n/superpowers:verification-before-completion\n\nWhen to use it: You have implemented version one, but you need to do systematic acceptance \"before you say it is done\": run tests, boundary checks, performance, lint, types, manual smoke test.\nGood for: Any PR pre-merge/pre-delivery.\n\nOne sentence to distinguish:\nTDD = Development Method\nverification = pre-delivery checklist\n\n4 Debugging related: specially used to \"locate problems\"\n\n/superpowers:systematic-debugging\n\nWhen to use: There is a bug/error report/wrong behavior, and you want to use a structured way to locate it: Reproduce → Narrow the scope → Hypothesis → Experiment → Repair → Prevent recurrence.\nDon’t mess with anyone: TDD (TDD is prevention and design, debugging is post-event positioning)\n\n5 Code Review Related: One Pair (Request vs Receive)\n\n/superpowers:requesting-code-review\n\nWhen to use it: You are going to send a PR/let others see it, and you want AI to help you: write a description of the PR, list the risk points, tell the reviewer where to look, and provide test methods.\n\n/superpowers:receiving-code-review\n\nWhen to use: When you receive review comments (or AI simulated review), you need to: Classify (must change/recommend change/no change) → respond one by one → make changes on the ground.\n\n6 Branch/finishing related: partial project management\n\n/superpowers:finishing-a-development-branch\n\nWhen to use: A feature branch needs to be finished: rebase/merge, clean up commits, update changelog, add documentation, and ensure CI green.\n\n/superpowers:using-git-worktrees\n\nWhen to use: You want to open multiple branches for development at the same time, but you don’t want to mess up dependencies by git checkout back and forth. For example: one worktree repairs the hotfix, and the other continues the main function.\n\n7 User Guide/Skill Library\n\n/superpowers:using-superpowers\n\nWhen to use: When you are not sure which command to choose, use this \"Navigation/General Instructions\".\n\n/superpowers:writing-skills\n\nWhen to use it: You want to \"create/edit a skill (or project specification)\", such as writing team agreements, coding style, test specifications, PR rules, etc.\n\nComplete process developed with Superpowers\n\nUncertain idea\n↓\n/superpowers:brainstorming ←───┐\n↓ │\nThe needs are clear │ Come back anytime if there is a problem\n↓ │\n/superpowers:writing-plans ←───┘\n↓\nThe task is broken down\n↓\n├─→ /superpowers:using-git-worktrees (multi-branch parallel environment)\n│\n├─→ /superpowers:subagent-driven-development (large functional division of labor)\n│ ↓\n│ /superpowers:test-driven-development (TDD mode)\n│ ↓\n│ Encountered bugs during development → /superpowers:systematic-debugging\n│└─→ /superpowers:dispatching-parallel-agents (independent task parallelism)\n↓\nor /superpowers:executing-plans (advance as planned)\n↓\nfinished\n↓\n/superpowers:verification-before-completion\n↓\n/superpowers:requesting-code-review\n↓\nReceive feedback → /superpowers:receiving-code-review\n↓\n/superpowers:finishing-a-development-branch\n↓\nMerge successful"}'::jsonb) WHERE id = 7;

UPDATE articles SET translations = jsonb_build_object('en', '{"title": "Reveal Ryan''s true face.", "summary": "​Teacher Ryan from the School of International Education of Zhengzhou University of Light Industry gave me a passing grade of 60 points at the end of the English semester. I went to ask why.\nAfter his operation:\n1. I misread it as 94, but the actual number is 60.\n2. Threaten me to change 60 to 59\n3. He said that if he were a Chinese teacher, I wouldn’t be so entangled.\n...", "content": "​Teacher Ryan from the School of International Education of Zhengzhou University of Light Industry gave me a passing grade of 60 points at the end of the English semester. I went to ask why.\nAfter his operation:\n1. I misread it as 94, but the actual number is 60.\n2. Threaten me to change 60 to 59\n3. He said that if he were a Chinese teacher, I wouldn’t be so entangled.\n4. Delete my WeChat\nMy operation:\n1. Inform the instructor, Academic Affairs Office, and Dean of various matters\n2. Check the marked grades (62 for normal times and 58 for the final period)\n\nThe final result is:\nFollow the teacher’s subjective wishes:\nMy English final exam performance was not good, and I had a series of problems with my pronunciation fluency.\nAnd other teachers don’t have a suitable method to quantify their achievements.\nthus giving up\n\nI hope everyone will take warning and take precautions in advance (including backup of class and exam recordings)\n\nI hope the teacher will not harass girls and favor girls over boys!"}'::jsonb) WHERE id = 9;

UPDATE articles SET translations = jsonb_build_object('en', '{"title": "Things to do as a college student", "summary": "TO (applies in all cases):\nfitness, study\nT1 (must do if you want to make progress): English, product thinking (science and engineering), vibe coding (liberal arts), groom yourself, sleep, disenchant big people, quit sex\nT2 (long-term benefit): Learn to obtain external network content and learn various...", "content": "TO (applies in all cases):\nfitness, study\nT1 (must do if you want to make progress): English, product thinking (science and engineering), vibe coding (liberal arts), groom yourself, sleep, disenchant big people, quit sex\nT2 (long-term benefit): Learn to access external network content, learn how to use various tools and software (Gemini/chatgpt, claude code), listen to music, economics, and quit pornography.\nT3 (useful when useful, useless when not): socialize, build good relationships, use Xiaohongshu, browse Reddit/Zhihu/Twitter, travel, and sing in KTV\nT4 (useless): Use TikTok, play games, overeat, play scripts, watch variety shows, read online novels, and gossip."}'::jsonb) WHERE id = 10;

